    "category": "Parent Guidance",
    "excerpt": "The internet is a normal part of childhood now. Here is how to make it safer without making it feel like a punishment.",
    "metaDescription": "Practical guide to online safety for kids. Learn what risks to watch for by age, how to set up parental controls, and how to keep communication open.",
    "content": "<p>The internet has become as much a part of childhood as playgrounds and school runs. Children are growing up online in a way no previous generation has experienced, and while that brings real opportunities, it also brings risks that most parents feel underprepared for.</p><h2>Why Online Safety Matters More Than Ever</h2><p>Children in the UK spend an average of three to four hours online every day. By the time a child is twelve, most have encountered content online that has made them uncomfortable. What helps is understanding the specific risks your child faces at their age, having open conversations, and putting simple structures in place.</p><h2>Key Risks by Age</h2><p><strong>Ages 4-7:</strong> Accidental exposure to upsetting content through YouTube autoplay, gaming platforms, and image searches. Priority is supervision and simple rules.</p><p><strong>Ages 8-11:</strong> Children begin using devices privately. They start creating accounts, joining group chats, and communicating outside the family. Conversations about online behaviour and privacy need to begin.</p><p><strong>Ages 12-16:</strong> Social media, gaming communities, and messaging apps dominate. Risks shift to cyberbullying, contact from strangers, and psychological effects of social comparison. At this stage, parental relationships matter more than parental controls.</p><h2>Five Things You Can Do This Week</h2><p><strong>1. Audit the devices in your home.</strong> Go through every device your child uses and check what apps are installed and what privacy settings are in place. Do it together.</p><p><strong>2. Move screens to shared spaces.</strong> Devices used in bedrooms are harder to monitor. Moving screen time to living rooms significantly reduces late-night use.</p><p><strong>3. Set up Family Link or Screen Time.</strong> Both Google Family Link and Apple Screen Time allow you to set daily limits, approve app downloads, and see what your child has been doing online.</p><p><strong>4. Talk about strangers online.</strong> Explain that online, people are not always who they say they are, and that someone being kind does not mean they are safe.</p><p><strong>5. Create a family agreement.</strong> A simple written set of household rules about online use, agreed together, is more effective than any app or parental control.</p><h2>Keep the Door Open</h2><p>The single biggest predictor of whether a child will come to a parent when something goes wrong online is whether they believe they will be heard rather than punished. Make it clear, regularly and genuinely, that if something happens online they can always tell you.</p><div style=\"background:#F0FDF4;border:2px solid #0EA5A0;border-radius:12px;padding:24px 28px;margin:40px 0;\"><h3 style=\"color:#0B1F3A;margin-top:0;\">Shield Protect Your Family With Our Online Safety Courses</h3><p style=\"color:#374151;\">Our <strong>Family Anchor</strong> course gives you the knowledge and language to talk to your children about online safety at every age.</p><p style=\"color:#374151;margin-bottom:0;\"><a href=\"/packages\" style=\"color:#0EA5A0;font-weight:600;\">Explore Our Courses</a></p></div>"
